1. What is a neural network?¶

A neural network takes an input, passes it through multiple layers of hidden neurons (mini-functions with unique coefficients that must be learned), and outputs a prediction representing the combined input of all the neurons. Neural Networks consist of the following components

1-) An input layer, x
2-) An arbitrary amount of hidden layers
3-) An output layer, ŷ
4-) A set of weights and biases between each layer, W and b
5-) A choice of activation function for each hidden layer.

1.1 Example of a neural network architecture: 4-Layer neural network¶

Let us construct a four-layer network (input, 2-hidden layers, output) Source: [https://towardsdatascience.com/]

1-) Input layer - 64 neurons (input image array)
2-)Hidden layer 1 - 128 neurons (arbitrary)
3-) Hidden layer 2 - 128 neurons (arbitrary)
4-) A set of weights and biases between each layer, W and b
5-) Output layer - 10 neurons (output one-hot array)

Hint¶

The activation function for the output layer should be softmax if you have a multiclass classification problem, a sigmoid if you have a binary classification problem or linear if you have a regression problem.

2. Activation functions¶

2.1 Sigmoid function¶

$${\displaystyle f(x)={\frac {1}{1+e^{-x}}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle f'(x) = f(x)\cdot(1-f(x))}$$
In [2]:
def plot_activation(input_data, func, dfunc, name="sigmoid"):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.title(name, fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel('z', fontsize=15)
    plt.ylabel('Activation function value', fontsize=15)
    sns.set_style("whitegrid")
    plt.plot(input_data, func, label="f (z)")
    plt.plot(input_data, dfunc, label="f '(z)")
    plt.legend(loc=4, prop={'size': 15}, frameon=True,shadow=True, facecolor="white", edgecolor="black")
    plt.savefig(name + ".png")
    plt.show()
    return
In [9]:
z = np.arange(-20, 20, 0.02)
f = 1/(1 + np.exp(-z))
df = f*(1 - f)
plot_activation(z, f, df, "Sigmoid")

2.2 ReLU¶

$${\displaystyle f(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{ if } x<0 \\ x & \text{ if } x\geq x \end{cases}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle f(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{ if } x<0 \\ 1 & \text{ if } x\geq x \end{cases}}$$
In [10]:
z = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.01)
f = z * (z > 0)
df = 1. * (z > 0)
plot_activation(z, f, df, "ReLU")

2.3 Tanh¶

$${\displaystyle f(x) = \operatorname {tgh} x={\frac {\sinh x}{\cosh x}}={\frac {e^{x}-e^{-x}}{e^{x}+e^{-x}}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle f'(x) = 1 - f(x)^{2}}$$
In [11]:
z = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.01)
f = np.tanh(z)
df = 1 - f*f
plot_activation(z, f, df, "tanh")

LeakyReLU¶

$${\displaystyle f(x) = \begin{cases} 0.01 \cdot x & \text{ if } x<0 \\ x & \text{ if } x\geq x \end{cases}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle f(x) = \begin{cases} 0.01 & \text{ if } x<0 \\ 1 & \text{ if } x\geq x \end{cases}}$$
In [12]:
z = np.arange(-10, 10, 0.01)
f = np.where(z > 0, z, z * 0.01)
df = np.where(z > 0, 1, 0.01)
plot_activation(z, f, df, "Leaky_ReLU")

3. Feed forward part¶

3.1 Initialize the weights and biases¶

1-) Randomly initialize the weights. The values should never be zero but closer to zero. 
2-) It is good to have positive as well as negative values so that apart from magnitude, direction also differs. 
3-) Normal distribution is a good choice. 
4-) Initializing bias vectors to zero is fine.

3.2 Feed-forward process¶

$${\displaystyle c={{(input \cdot weights) + bias}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle a1= f1(c)}$$

3.2.1 Example code¶

In [13]:
def feed_forward(x, Wh, Wo):
    # Hidden layer
    Zh = x * Wh
    H = activation_function(Zh)

    # Output layer
    Zo = H * Wo
    output = activation_function(Zo)
    return output

3.2.2 Feed forward equations: 4-Layer neural network¶

$${\displaystyle c1={{(X \cdot w1) + b1}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle a1= sigmoid(c1)}$$$${\displaystyle c2={{(a1 \cdot w2) + b2}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle a2= sigmoid(c2)}$$$${\displaystyle c3={{(a2 \cdot w3) + b3}}} \hspace{1cm} {\displaystyle a3= softmax(c3)}$$

4. Backpropogation¶

Back-propagation computes the error from the output of feed-forward and the true value. This error is back-propagated to all the weight matrices through computing gradients in each layer and these weights are updated.

4.1 Loss function¶

Generally speaking, the loss function is designed to show how far we are from the 'ideal' solution.

4.1.1 Code¶

In [3]:
def compute_loss_func(self, y_pred, y_real): 
        if self.cost_name=="MSE":
            e=np.mean(np.power(y_real-y_pred, 2))
            e_prime= 2*(y_pred-y_real)/y_real.size
        #−(ylog(p)+(1−y)log(1−p))
        # −∑yo,clog(po,c)
        elif self.cost_name=="cross_entropy":     
            n_samples = y_real.shape[0]
            #y_real.argmax(axis=1) returns the indices of 
            logp = - np.log(y_pred[np.arange(n_samples), y_real.argmax(axis=1)])
            #log_likelihood = -np.log(p[range(a),y_true])
            e = np.sum(logp)/n_samples
            #p[range(a),y_true] -= 1
            e_prime = 0
        else:
            raise ValueError('Cost function is not supported')
        return e, e_prime

4.1.2 Binary entropy¶

M - number of classes (dog, cat, fish)

log - the natural log

y - binary indicator (0 or 1) if class label c is the correct classification for observation o

p - predicted probability observation o is of class c

src: https://ml-cheatsheet.readthedocs.io/en/latest/loss_functions.html

$$-\left(y\log(p) + (1-y)\log(1-p)\right)$$

4.1.3 Cross entropy¶

$$-\sum_{c=1}^My_{o,c}\log(p_{o,c})$$

4.1.3 MSE¶

$$MSE=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}^n (y_i - \hat{y_i})^2$$

4.2 Backpropogation equation: Example- 4 Layer network¶

Equation 1: W3¶

$$\frac{dcost}{dw3}= \frac{dcost}{da3} \cdot \frac{da3}{dc3} \cdot \frac{dc3}{dw3}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

Where:

$${ c3={{(a2 \cdot w3) + b3}}} \hspace{1cm} {a3= softmax(c3)}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$
  1. $$\frac{dc3}{dw3}=a2$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

  2. $$\frac{da3}{dc3}={dsoftmax(c3)}$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

  3. $$\frac{dcost}{da3}=\frac{-y}{a3}$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

Hint: Product of cross_entropy' * softmax'= predicted value — real value¶

Equation 1: W3¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$$\frac{dcost}{dw3}= {a2} \cdot ({a3-y})$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

Update equation: W3¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$${w3}= {w3} - \frac{dcost}{dw3}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

with: $$a3\_delta=({a3-y})$$

Equation 1: b3¶

$$\frac{dcost}{db3}= \frac{dcost}{da3} \cdot \frac{da3}{dc3} \cdot \frac{dc3}{db3}$$
  1. $$\frac{dcost}{da3} \cdot \frac{da3}{dc3}= ({a3-y})$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$
  2. $$\frac{dc3}{db3}=1$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

Equation 1: b3¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$$\frac{dcost}{db3}= ({a3-y})$$

Update equation: W3¶

${b3}= {b3} - \frac{dcost}{db3}$

Equation 2: W2¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$$\frac{dcost}{dw2}= \frac{dcost}{da2} \cdot \frac{da2}{dc2} \cdot \frac{dc2}{dw2}$$

Where: $$c2={{(a1\cdot w2) + b2}}$$

$$a2=sigmoid(c2)$$
  1. $$\frac{dc2}{dw2}=a1$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$
  2. $$\frac{da2}{dc2}={dsigmoid(c2)}$$

or

  1. $$\frac{dcost}{da2}=\frac{dcost}{da3}\cdot \frac{da3}{dc3}\cdot \frac{dc3}{da2}= ({a3-y})\cdot{w3}$$
$$\hspace{1cm}$$

Hint: Product of cross_entropy' * softmax'= predicted value — real value

Equation 1: W2¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$$\frac{dcost}{dw2}= {a1} \cdot ({a3-y})\cdot {w3} \cdot {dsigmoid(c2)} $$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

Update equation: W2¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$${w2}= {w2} - \frac{dcost}{dw2}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

with: $$a2\_delta=(({a3-y})\cdot {w3} \cdot {dsigmoid(c2)})$$¶

Equation 2: b2¶

$$\frac{dcost}{db2}= \frac{dcost}{da2} \cdot \frac{da2}{dc2} \cdot \frac{dc2}{db2}$$
  1. $$\frac{dcost}{da3} \cdot \frac{da3}{dc3}= ({a3-y})$$
  2. $$\frac{dc3}{db3}=1$$

Equation 2: b2¶

$$\frac{dcost}{db3}= ({a3-y})\cdot {w3} \cdot {dsigmoid(c2)}$$

Update equation: b2¶

$${b2}= {b2} - \frac{dcost}{db2}$$$${b2}= {b2} - (({a3-y})\cdot {w3} \cdot {dsigmoid(c2)})$$

Equation 3: W1¶

$$\frac{dcost}{dw1}= \frac{dcost}{da1} \cdot \frac{da1}{dc1} \cdot \frac{dc1}{dw1}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

Where: $$\hspace{1cm}$$ $${c1={(input\cdot w1) + b1}} \hspace{1cm} a1=sigmoid(c1)$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

  1. $$\frac{dc1}{dw1}=input$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$
  2. $$\frac{da1}{dc1}={dsigmoid(c1)}$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

or

  1. $$\frac{dcost}{da1}=\frac{dcost}{da2}\cdot \frac{da2}{dc2}\cdot \frac{dc2}{da1}= ({a2\_delta})\cdot{w2}$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

Update equation: W1¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$${w2}= {w1} - \frac{dcost}{dw1}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$

with: $$a1\_delta=\frac{dcost}{da1} \cdot \frac{da1}{dc1}$$ $$\hspace{1cm}$$

Update equation: b1¶

$$\hspace{1cm}$$$${b1}= {b1} - \frac{dcost}{db1}$$$$\hspace{1cm}$$$${b1}= {b1} - (a1\_delta)$$

class neural_networks:

        def __init__(self, x, y, layers=[128, 128,10], **kwargs):

            #self.activation_name = kwargs.pop('activation_name', 'ReLu')
            self.cost_name = kwargs.pop('cost_function_name', 'cross_entropy')
            self.input= x
            self.output=y 
            #learning rate 
            self.learning_rate=0.5
            super(neural_networks, self).__init__()
            #the size of the input
            self.input_size=x.shape[1]
            #the size of the output 
            self.output_size=y.shape[1]
             #initialize the weights for one layer, matrix (input_layer, output_layer) 
            self.weights = [np.random.randn(self.input_size, layers[0])]
            #initialize the biases for one layer, vector (1, output_layer)
            self.biases=[np.zeros((1,layers[0]))]

            for i in range (len(layers)-1):
                self.weights.append(np.random.randn(layers[i], layers[i+1]))
                self.biases.append(np.zeros((1,layers[i+1])))
            self.weights=np.asarray(self.weights)
            for i in range (len(layers)):
                self.biases[i]=np.asarray(self.biases[i])

        def compute_activ_func(self, x, activation_name): 
            self.activation_name=activation_name
            if self.activation_name=="ReLu": 
                # Rectified linear function, which outputs the max between 0 and x 
                y=np.maximum(0,x)
                y_prime=np.where(x <= 0, 0, 1)
            elif self.activation_name=="Sigmoid": 
                    #Sigmoid function, squishes the input between 0 and 1 
                y=1/(1 + np.exp(-x))
                y_prime=y * (1 - y)
            elif self.activation_name=="Softmax": 
                  #normalizes the input into a probability distribution consisting of K probabilities, which sum to 1
                exps = np.exp(x - np.max(x, axis=1, keepdims=True))
                y=exps/np.sum(exps, axis=1, keepdims=True)
                y1=y.reshape(-1,1)
                y_prime= np.diagflat(y1) - np.dot(y1, y1.T)
            elif self.activation_name=="linear": 
                y=x 
                y_prime=1
            elif self.activation_name=="tanh":
                # tanh function outputs number between -1 and 1 
                y=np.tanh(x)
                y_prime=1-np.tanh(x)**2
            else: 
                raise ValueError('Activation function is not supported')
            return y, y_prime 

        
        def compute_loss_func(self, y_pred, y_real): 
            if self.cost_name=="MSE":
                e=np.mean(np.power(y_real-y_pred, 2))
                e_prime= 2*(y_pred-y_real)/y_real.size
            #−(ylog(p)+(1−y)log(1−p))
            # −∑yo,clog(po,c)
            elif self.cost_name=="cross_entropy":     
                n_samples = y_real.shape[0]
                #y_real.argmax(axis=1) returns the indices of 
                logp = - np.log(y_pred[np.arange(n_samples), y_real.argmax(axis=1)])
                #log_likelihood = -np.log(p[range(a),y_true])
                e = np.sum(logp)/n_samples
                #p[range(a),y_true] -= 1
                e_prime = 0
            else:
                raise ValueError('Cost function is not supported')
            return e, e_prime
  
        

        def feedforward(self):
            z1 = np.dot(self.input, self.weights[0]) + self.biases[0]
            self.a1= self.compute_activ_func(z1, activation_name="Sigmoid")[0]
            z2 = np.dot(self.a1, self.weights[1]) + self.biases[1]
            self.a2=self.compute_activ_func(z2, activation_name="Sigmoid")[0]
            z3 = np.dot(self.a2, self.weights[2]) +self.biases[2]
            self.a3=self.compute_activ_func(z3, activation_name="Softmax")[0]
        def backpropagation(self):
            loss=self.compute_loss_func(self.a3, self.output)[0]
            print('Error :', loss)
            a3_delta = (self.a3- self.output)/self.output.shape[0] # w3
            z2_delta = np.dot(a3_delta, self.weights[2].T)
            a2_delta = z2_delta * self.compute_activ_func(self.a2, activation_name="Sigmoid")[1] # w2
            z1_delta = np.dot(a2_delta, self.weights[1].T)
            a1_delta = z1_delta * self.compute_activ_func(self.a1, activation_name="Sigmoid")[1] # w1

            self.weights[2] -= self.learning_rate * np.dot(self.a2.T, a3_delta)
            self.biases[2] -= self.learning_rate * np.sum(a3_delta, axis=0, keepdims=True)
            self.weights[1] -= self.learning_rate * np.dot(self.a1.T, a2_delta)
            self.biases[1]  -= self.learning_rate * np.sum(a2_delta, axis=0)
            self.weights[0] -= self.learning_rate * np.dot(self.input.T, a1_delta)
            self.biases[0] -= self.learning_rate * np.sum(a1_delta, axis=0)
        def train(self, epochs, **kwargs):
            for i in range(epochs):
                self.feedforward()
                self.backpropagation()
            
        def prediction(self, new_data):
            self.input=new_data 
            self.feedforward()
            predictions= self.a3.argmax()
            return predictions

        def get_acc(self, x, y):
                acc = 0
                for xx,yy in zip(x, y):
                    s = self.prediction(xx)
                    if s == np.argmax(yy):
                        acc +=1
                return acc/len(x)*100

import torch
import torchvision
import torch.optim as optim
from torch import nn
from torch.autograd import Variable
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader
from torchvision import transforms
from torchvision.utils import save_image
from torchvision.datasets import MNIST

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np


class NetClassifier(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(NetClassifier, self).__init__()
        self.hidden_layer1 = nn.Linear(28*28, 128)
        self.hidden_layer2 = nn.Linear(128, 128)
        self.output_layer = nn.Linear(128, 10)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = x.view(-1, 28*28)
        x = torch.sigmoid(self.hidden_layer1(x))
        x = torch.sigmoid(self.hidden_layer2(x))
        x = self.output_layer(x) # I do not add the softmax as it is tackled in the CrossEntropyLoss
        return x
    
model = NetClassifier()

# optimization

criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=0.001, momentum=0.9)

def train_net(net, data, max_epochs=10):
       
    for epoch in range(max_epochs):        
        for data in dataloader:
            X_batch, y_batch = data
            inputs = Variable(X_batch)
            # zero the parameter gradients
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            # forward + backward + optimize
            outputs = net(inputs)
            loss = criterion(outputs, y_batch)
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()
            
        # ===================log========================
        
        print('epoch [{}/{}], loss:{:.4f}'

correct = 0
total = 0
with torch.no_grad():
    for data in dataloader:
        images, labels = data
        outputs = model(images)
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        total += labels.size(0)
        correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

print('Accuracy of the network on the 10000 test images: %d %%' % (
    100 * correct / total))

import torch
import torchvision
import torch.optim as optim
from torch import nn
from torch.autograd import Variable
from torch.utils.data import DataLoader
from torch.utils.data import TensorDataset

torch.manual_seed(1)    # reproducible results

# Create synthetic data
def generate_data(n_samples):
    epsilon = np.random.normal(size=(n_samples))
    y_data = np.random.uniform(-10.5, 10.5, n_samples)
    x_data = 7*np.sin(0.75*y_data) + 0.5*y_data + epsilon
    return x_data, y_data

In [31]:
# Train network
def train_regression_network(loader, regression_model):
    for epoch in range(max_epochs):
        for step, (batch_x, batch_y) in enumerate(loader): # for each training step

            x_batch = Variable(batch_x)
            y_batch = Variable(batch_y)

            prediction = regression_model(x_batch)     # input x and predict based on x
            loss = criterion(prediction, y_batch)     # must be (1. nn output, 2. target)

            optimizer.zero_grad()   # clear gradients for next train
            loss.backward()         # backpropagation, compute gradients
            optimizer.step()        # apply gradients


        print('epoch [{}/{}], loss:{:.4f}'
                .format(epoch+1, max_epochs, loss.item()))

        if epoch % 4 == 0:
            # plot and show learning process           
            fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,6))
            ax.set_title('Regression', fontsize=12)
            ax.set_xlabel('Independent variable', fontsize=12)
            ax.set_ylabel('Dependent variable', fontsize=12)
            ax.set_xlim(-15.0, 15.0)
            ax.set_ylim(-15.0, 15.0)
            ax.scatter(x_batch.data.numpy(), y_batch.data.numpy(), color = "blue", alpha=0.2)
            ax.scatter(x_batch.data.numpy(), prediction.data.numpy(), color='green', alpha=0.5)
            ax.text(5.0, -10.0, 'Epoch = %d' % epoch,
                    fontdict={'size': 18, 'color':  'red'})
            ax.text(5.0, -12.0, 'Loss = %.4f' % loss.data.numpy(),
                    fontdict={'size': 18, 'color':  'red'})

            plt.show()

    print('End training')
